snippet.textDisplay:
When the game first released I couldn't get into it at all and thought it was too hard stopped playing since

After playing again now it's not hard at all just be patient and be aggressive as possible also holding down sprint button as you fight helps a lot too (especially when fighting against the giant monkeys bosses) you can easily get behind enemies and constantly attacking them 

Here's a tip, hold block button in fights and tap when they attack to deflect and when you see the red icon either jump on their head or counter

snippet.textDisplay:
Man, I will never forget the feeling of first beating Sword Saint Ishiin. What. A. Rush. Felt like I was gonna have a heart attack üòÇ Makes you feel like a God after, though. 

Now I play his memory for fun, same with Inner Ishiin's memory. Being able to just stomp him whenever you feel like is such a rewarding feeling üòÖ Easily the best, most rewarding boss and arguably one of the best games I have ever played. Absolute masterpiece of a game. 

If you're stuck, take a break, but always come back and keep at it. Persistence is key, learn the moveset patterns by parrying and dodging accordingly. If all else fails, look up some boss guides here on yt, no shame in that for the sake of progression. Try not to cheese if you don't have to though :/ 

There is no easy mode for this game, only a grind to git gud.

snippet.textDisplay: I went looking at sekiro 1 star reviews and basically every single one was just people crying that the game was ‚Äútoo hard‚Äù or ‚Äújanky and inconsistent‚Äù. Meanwhile I think Im on new game plus 9 and after my second run I could basically parry only every boss. Sekiro has the highest learning curve but by no means is the game ‚Äúunfair‚Äù. Once you understand the mechanics the game is essentially in your control and as long as you don‚Äôt just panic parry and dodge spam you will be fine. You hardly have to move in sekiro I have beaten bosses standing still so it simply can‚Äôt be that hard. The last clip is a perfect example of how you could exploit the bosses in sekiro it‚Äôs actually how I beat owl the first timeüòÇ

snippet.textDisplay:
Your first fight with genichiro will 100% help you become a better player in my eyes, he has a solid mix of attacks and has you always on your toes until ofc he likes to jus walk around n stare at you lmao. 

I struggled on my first play through and second because I chose both east endings and ofc had to fight ishinn. Upon completing both easy endings, I decided it was time I took the game serious and platinumed it so I spent every day playing it until I got into NG+5 and had platinumed the game. 

I own the shura, Tengu and the Ashina skins. In my honest opinion you need to pay more attention if you‚Äôre struggling on bosses like inner owl or hell even Emma. 

You need to understand what attacks your opponent is going to throw out and how to counter properly, play as agro as you can but don‚Äôt be stupid. Throw two light hits then expect an attack back you can parry. Don‚Äôt use thrust attacks tbh it jus sucks, utilise the correct shinobi art for the right enemy like ichimonji double against ishinn or high monk for high posture damage. 

Use good shinobi prosthetics like firecracker or an axe. You can make combos using Sakura dance and combining it with tools which imo look really cool although not necessary.

I think Sekiro is easy compared to most souls games tbh. Like, let's compare hard mode Sekiro vs hard mode Elden Ring and the difference is night and day. 
Sekiro's hard mode still feels like a rhythm game with loose timing; meanwhile you're there in Elden Ring, swinging for hours cause you're unarmed against a god.
If Sekiro let you beat the game as the unarmed pleb you were at the start, then we can start talking.

snippet.textDisplay:
At one point it just stopped being difficult for me, around when I beat sword saint isshin, then the game just clicked and I could consistenly beat isshin without even resurrecting or dying, I beat inner isshin, Owl (father), Inner Father all first try and did every gauntlet of strength aside from mortal journey.
I got too good at the game and it wasn't hard anymore and I could beat the game only dying twice, and both times were to gravity.  I 100% the game in only 24 hours.
And since that moment I've gotten better at every souls game, playing monster hunter: world probably helped with that too, I brought the knowledge from that into the souls games and realized you can just walk around a lot of attacks.  I recently 100% ds3 as well, only games I haven't 100% is ds2 and demon souls, ds2 is just going to take awhile because all the achievements left is obtaining all the spells of every type, and Demon's Souls because I just don't even have the game

snippet.textDisplay:
Dunno if anyone has said about this, but
the last part is actually a legitimate method to trick the enemy's AI to do what you want them to do. Thing is, AI in this game has specific moves to perform after they successfully deflect (or parry) player's attack, you'll notice when you keep attacking an enemy in a combo, mostly the 3rd attack will get deflected and the enemy will perform what I'd called "counterattack" and player will most likely be forced to take defensive action. We can exploit this "counterattack" thingy by doing an impaling move (holding the attack button), this move can only be deflected(or parried) to negate the damage or else you'll get direct damage and by this logic, the game won't let players dealing direct damage to enemies that easily, so most enemies tend to deflect this move instead of blocking it, which then lead to enemy performing a "counterattack" because they deflected player's attack. and if we know what move they'll "counterattack", we can prepare ourselves according to it because it is very predictable.

snippet.textDisplay:
Cool video now here's a way to defeat sister fredie easily: Friede turns invisible and jumps across the arena (if you are close to her, invisibility is turned off). After a few seconds there is a sound and she performs a swift attack (which can be broken, if player attacks her before she moves to perform visceral attack), in which she grabs the player with her scythe and throws them beneath her. Deals high damage, but with good timing can be avoided. If player is not good at timing, he can either¬†hit Friede with kukri/arrow, which are visible even if boss is invisible or poison her. Sorcerers can also use homing spells.Jump + FreezingFriede jumps in the¬†air and tries to land on player. After landing a circle of ice appears, which explodes after a second dealing serious frost damage.¬†Freeze JumpFriede freeze arena directly in front of her, then jumps on player dealing both frost and psychical damage and causes ice path to explode. If she lands far from that path, it gives a good opportunity to perform backstab attack.Freeze attackSister Friede freezes the ground in front of her at¬†medium range, in a triangle-like shape. Walking on it causes frost damage. After a few seconds it explodes and causes massive frost damage. Can be avoided with ease.Scythe SwingsFriede swings¬†three times, dealing both physical and magic damage. Can cause Frostbite effect. Simply roll away from her.Scythe Swing + JumpFriede attacks with her scythe and jumps back to avoid being hit.Healing (2nd battle phase)Friede, after a short preparation, restores some of the hp lost during the¬†battle. Hit her with any weapon to break the spell.

Second Phase (3rd battle phase) - In this phase Friede uses Dark Pyromancy and is labeled as Darkflame Friede. She uses a few attacks from her first phase, but they are now more powerful.

¬†¬†Second¬†Phase (3rd¬†battle phase)Blackflame flying smash + homing snakeOften the first move she does in phase three. Friede¬†goes up with black fireworks, comes down with a smashing AoE and a homing flame snake. Keep running left or right and after the first smash part, run behind her and backstab.Two invisible ice waves + big blackflame snakeThe first ice wave lets you know where she is and the second ice wave lets you know if she is going left or right. If the second ice wave attack happens left from the place she did the first one, she jumps left again and will be helplessly charging the blackflame snake somewhere left, providing an easy backstab opportunity.Fast dash to decapitating grabWhile in medium distance from you, Friede's¬†blue scythe flashes and she dashes towards you, grabbing you in a guillotine attack. Dodge the grab a little left and towards her to end up behind her for the backstab.Long combo to small jumping smashFriede starts with a small jump and keeps swinging multiple times until she finishes with a small and fast jumping smash. Dodge the last move towards her and go for the backstab if you can.Scythe grab + HitBlackflame Friede tries to bring player closer with her scyte, then she swiftly attack dealing both Fire and Physical damage. Rolling from her is a good strategy to avoid damage.Quick healingVery rarely, Blackflame Friede may restore some healthpoints.

Father Ariandel -¬†Second Battle phase Only

snippet.textDisplay:
This is a game in which you need to master the basic mechanics: perry, dash, block and attack, after that everything becomes a question of  concentration and persistence.

You can always do some strategies and tricks, but mastering basic skills wins over any challenge, that's the kind of game Sekiro is.

snippet.textDisplay: as a pro soul series player I can assure you that sekiro was a *NIGHTMARE* due to the sudden change in controls and battle tactics. unlike other souls game where you have a fighting style based around your build, sekiro pressures you to fight like a shinobi and it's mainly focused around timing and control, IT DOESN'T MAKE IT EASY TO CHANGE MY FIGHTING STYLE!!!! I am the type of player who would bombarded the enemy with projectiles and spells while dashing in and deal Swift blows. sekiro May have been quite the headache in the beginning ( due to sudden change in controls and me being a dumbass and not reading the item discripation, like literally it could have saved me 3 hours if I read that devine confetti works wonder against dead enemies like shichimin warrior or headless) but after you learned how the controls work, perfected your timing and carefully analysed your opponent's pattern it gets a bit easier (no way the game gets easier by just this much. do you know how many times I died against that f@cking ape just for him to become Miyamoto Musashi and tear my a$$ into pieces) but that's what makes it enjoyable. it's not just centered around fights, it has a lot of different mechanics that I personally love. exploring the beautiful world of sekiro, finding treasures and hidden bosses like different headless, finding hidden mechanics like the devine child's tears,a wide variety of upgrades, arts, skills,jutsus, items etc. but the thing I like the most about sekiro is the decision making. I am a big fan of decision making games like undertale because it increases my impact on the story. normally you would play the game and would like be given a pre-designed ending but in sekiro my decision influence the ending making me feel like it's not a avatar that I am controlling but I myself am the character. all in all sekiro is a 10/10 in my opinion.

snippet.textDisplay: Sekiro is one of the few games that, outside of maybe one or two instances, tries really hard to create fights that show you where you messed up, on top of their enemy design being just amazing. The difference between the invading forces, which are all highly aggressive, and the Ashina forces, which are all extremely defense oriented is an amazing detail, same with the difference between Guardian ape's phase one and phase two, where you're fighting a gorilla in phase one, and in phase two you fight what is literally a bug in a gorilla costume struggling to make it's own body function in a way that it can understand and utilize. Sekiro is a genuine masterpiece, even if sometimes the bosses have a brain aneurysm and forget that how to do more than one attack.
snippet.textOriginal: Sekiro is one of the few games that, outside of maybe one or two instances, tries really hard to create fights that show you where you messed up, on top of their enemy design being just amazing. The difference between the invading forces, which are all highly aggressive, and the Ashina forces, which are all extremely defense oriented is an amazing detail, same with the difference between Guardian ape's phase one and phase two, where you're fighting a gorilla in phase one, and in phase two you fight what is literally a bug in a gorilla costume struggling to make it's own body function in a way that it can understand and utilize. Sekiro is a genuine masterpiece, even if sometimes the bosses have a brain aneurysm and forget that how to do more than one attack.

snippet.textDisplay:
Sekiro was easily the most difficult Fromsoft game i've played, but when that gameplay loop finally clicked? Absolute perfection.

It's still not my favorite game they've put out, I just love the worldbuilding of the Souls trilogy and their more traditional RPG elements too much, but the flow of Sekiro's gameplay is unmatched. And how they re-used Genichiro's fight as a benchmark for the player's skill and a narrative rival for Wolf was beautiful. That was one of my favorite examples of blending gameplay and narrative in recent memory.
snippet.textOriginal:
